{{Use mdy dates|date = August 2019}}
[[File:National Days map.png|thumb|right|300px|{{legend|#008000|Independence-related National Day}} {{legend|#00FF00|Other [[National Day]]}} {{legend|#7F7F7F|No official National Day}}]]
An '''independence day''' is an annual event commemorating the [[anniversary]] of a [[nation]]'s independence or [[Sovereign state|statehood]], usually after ceasing to be a group or part of another nation or state, or more rarely after the end of a [[military occupation]]. Many countries commemorate their independence from a [[colonial empire]]. American political commentator [[Walter Russell Mead]] notes that, &quot;World-wide, British Leaving Day is never out of season.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;Walter Russell Mead, &quot;The Sun Ever Sets on the British Empire: Like the U.S., nations from Afghanistan to Zimbabwe celebrate ‘British Leaving Day.’&quot; [https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-sun-ever-sets-on-the-british-empire-11594076187 ''Wall Street Journal''] July 6, 2020].&lt;/ref&gt;

== List ==
The following list includes current [[United Nations General Assembly observers|observer]] and [[member states of the United Nations]] that have [[public holiday]]s dedicated to the establishment of the country's independence or sovereignty from a foreign power. The list does not include days commemorating regime changes (e.g. various [[Revolution Day]]s or [[Republic Day]]s), days commemorating its liberation from an occupying military power ([[Liberation Day]]s or [[Victory Day]]s), or other [[National Day]]s not tied to the establishment of independence.

